# Validation Discipline

How to verify things before trusting them. Consolidates 9 prior session-feedback rules (never-weaken-guardrails, read-knowledge-first, session-log-first, validate-review-findings, check-tool-layers, runtime-uat-catches-static, use-existing-harness-first, no-blame-toolchain, test-cold-path).

**Why this file exists:** These rules prevent the most expensive failure modes: shipping based on misread code, debating API behavior without probing, blaming the toolchain, or trusting automated review findings without checking them.

---

## 1. Never weaken guardrails

When CI or automation blocks you, **fix the root cause** ŌĆö never bypass, skip, or weaken the check.

**Banned reflexes:**
- `--no-verify` on commits
- `--no-gpg-sign`
- Admin bypass on branch protection
- Direct push past CI
- Disabling tests to go green
- Commenting out a failing assertion

**Why:** Weakened guardrails compound. Each "temporary" bypass becomes permanent and makes the next failure harder to catch. Yesterday's "we'll fix it after" is tomorrow's silent production regression.

**How to apply:** If a CI check or hook blocks, investigate *why*. If the check is wrong, fix the check. If the code is wrong, fix the code. Never patch around it.

---

## 2. Read knowledge files before querying external services

**Read the relevant knowledge file before any query to PostHog, Cloudflare, Sentry, or any other external system.**

**Why:** 2026-04-10 session queried TelemetryDeck (dead tool, not in our stack), used underscore event names instead of dot-separated (`app_launched` vs `app.launched`), and hit the sunset Cloudflare REST API instead of GraphQL. All three mistakes would have been avoided by reading `observability-operations.md` first.

**How to apply:**
- For any business scan, metrics query, or observability work: read `.claude/knowledge/observability-operations.md` first.
- It has the exact event names, API endpoints, and tool inventory.
- Do not rely on memory from prior sessions for event names or API formats.

---

## 3. Read session-log AND issue comments first

Before drafting, calling council, or accepting the issue body's diagnosis: grep `.claude/knowledge/session-log.md` for `#<N>` AND run `gh issue view <N> --comments`. This is Gate 0 in [workflow-process ┬¦1](./workflow-process.md#1-council--codex-required-for-every-code-change); hooks `check-issue-prior-context.sh` and `gate-gh-issue-view.sh` enforce.

**Incidents this prevents:**
- **#277, 2026-04-11** ŌĆö session-log noted PR #220 had *designed* a three-way paste flow; shipped code was two-way. Missing branch was the whole fix. Skipped the log ŌåÆ 2 council rounds on the wrong problem, ~40 min.
- **#329, 2026-04-17** ŌĆö `gh issue view --json body,title` filtered out comments; missed @m13v's caveat and the owner's adopted revision. PR 330 shipped wrong plan, closed, ~45 min.

Hooks catch the plan-file write, not every thought before it. If prior entries describe a design decision, verify shipped code matches the design before assuming the design is the bug.

---

## 4. Check all tool interface layers

Before using any tool you haven't used recently (CLI, MCP server, plugin, skill), check all its interface layers and pick the most direct one for the task.

**Why:** 2026-04-12 session used the `codex:rescue` plugin/skill for a code audit. The plugin's wrapper had zombie-process + Claude-interrupt-leakage bugs that cost ~30 min of debugging. Meanwhile `codex review --uncommitted` was a purpose-built CLI subcommand that would have bypassed the plugin entirely. An installed tool has multiple interface layers; having access isn't the same as knowing the right entry point.

**How to apply:**
- First step with a tool: `<tool> --help` and scan subcommands.
- Check for `mcp-server` / `mcp` subcommands ŌĆö MCP mode is the canonical Claude integration.
- Prefer direct CLI subcommands (e.g., `codex review`, `codex exec`) over plugin wrappers.
- Plugin skills are convenience wrappers ŌĆö use them when the underlying CLI is awkward, not by default.
- When a plugin misbehaves, don't retry or debug the wrapper. Check if the underlying tool has a cleaner entry point first.

---

## 5. Validate automated review findings against actual code

When code-review agents (Codex, `feature-dev:code-reviewer`, or overnight autonomous review) produce findings, validate each one against the real code before acting.

**Why:** 2026-04-05 overnight review produced 16 findings across heart and limb paths. Upon manual validation:
- TranscriptionPipeline "streaming cleanup" bug ŌĆö wrong (the catch block at line 288 DOES check `streamingASRActive` and calls `cancelStreaming`; the agent misread the defer ordering).
- PreRollForwarder "lock allocation" ŌĆö real rule violation but wrong impact claim (`drainRing` is only called from @MainActor, never from the RT audio thread).
- ASRManager "inFlightLoadTask race" ŌĆö wrong (cooperative scheduling on @MainActor means no true race).
- AudioServiceHandler "VAD stale state" ŌĆö wrong (`startVADMonitoring` creates a fresh task with local `processedSampleCount`).
- Only 4 of 8 limb findings were worth fixing.

**How to apply ŌĆö for each finding:**
1. Read the actual code at the cited lines.
2. Trace the execution path, not just the pattern.
3. Check whether the "bug" is actually handled by a different code path the reviewer missed.
4. For concurrency claims, verify the actor/thread isolation context.
5. Present validated findings to the user with honest confidence assessment *before* starting fixes.

---

## 6. Runtime UAT catches what static review misses

Static code review (Codex, council, re-reads) catches logic and interface issues. It cannot observe runtime behavior. **Always close the loop with end-to-end UAT on the running app before declaring a feature ship-ready.**

**Why:** 2026-04-12, Multilingual v1 epic ŌĆö Codex passed four review rounds on `LanguageDetector`. All tests passed. Build was clean. Then UAT with TTS across 7 non-English languages revealed the detector reliably returns `lang=en` with confidence 1.00 for clearly non-English audio. The softmax transform on WhisperKit's `langProbs` was the likely cause, but it only surfaced when real audio flowed through the stack. Italian and Tamil audio then hallucinated complete English garbage because the wrong-language hint was passed to transcribe. Without UAT, this would have shipped.

**How to apply:**
- Before declaring a language, audio, or ML feature complete, run real audio through the running app with `/wispr-rebuild-and-relaunch` + `record_tts()` or manual PTT.
- Cover the languages, accents, or modes the feature claims to support, not just the ones that worked first try.
- Test across backends (Parakeet AND WhisperKit) and modes (`.auto` AND `.locked`) where applicable.
- Check the app log (`~/Library/Logs/EnviousWispr/app.log`) for LID / polish / pipeline trace, not just the pasted transcript.
- Unit tests with mocked probability dicts do not substitute for real-audio testing. They verify the shape of the logic, not whether the integration with the upstream library works.

---

## 7. Use existing harness first

Before building new UAT infrastructure (TTS generation, audio routing, hotkey synthesis, clipboard capture), grep the knowledge base and `Tests/RuntimeUAT/` first.

**Existing battle-tested helpers in `Tests/RuntimeUAT/wispr_eyes.py`:**
- `tts(sentence, voice, engine)` ŌĆö OpenAI TTS primary, `say` fallback. Returns audio file path.
- `test_recording(audio, sentence, hold, expect, timeout)` ŌĆö end-to-end: menu Start/Stop, TTS + afplay, watches pipeline states, verifies clipboard. Uses menu-based recording (no hotkey synthesis needed).
- `test_hands_free(...)` ŌĆö hands-free mode test.
- `record_tts` ŌĆö convenience helper.

**Why:** 2026-04-12 wasted time writing a Python harness with custom TTS via urllib, BlackHole loopback routing (Saurabh stopped this ŌĆö wanted real speaker/mic, not synthetic loopback), and `Quartz.CGEventCreateKeyboardEvent` for right-Cmd synthesis ŌĆö which fails for modifier keys because macOS uses `flagsChanged` events, not `keyDown`. All unnecessary. `wispr_eyes.test_recording()` handles it with menu-based recording, TTS via existing `tts()` helper, real speaker audio, and clipboard watching baked in.

**How to apply:**
1. Any UAT-adjacent task: check `Tests/RuntimeUAT/wispr_eyes.py` FIRST. Recipes in [uat-testing.md](../knowledge/uat-testing.md).
2. Check `.claude/knowledge/archived-memories/` for prior learnings (e.g., `uat-ptt-key-simulation-v2-cgevent-flagschanged-simulation.md`).
3. Grep before writing: `grep -rl "TTS\|afplay\|Samantha\|openai" Tests/RuntimeUAT/`.
4. If a new helper is genuinely needed, add it to `wispr_eyes.py` so it's reusable.

---

## 8. No blame toolchain ŌĆö reproduce and read our code first

Do not attribute crashes, test failures, or unexpected behavior to Swift runtime bugs, toolchain issues, or "known platform bugs" without first reproducing the issue and reading the actual code path.

**Why:** 2026-04-05, a `Fatal error: Range requires lowerBound <= upperBound` crash in the test suite was blamed on "Swift Testing runtime bug with parameterized tests on arm64e." Three different workarounds were tried (converting parameterized tests to loops, adding `.serialized` traits). None worked ŌĆö the actual cause was `for j in 1...0` in `WERCalculator.swift` when `hypothesis` was empty. A plain off-by-one range bug. Saurabh: "you are fast to blame others when it's often a fundamental lack of understanding."

**How to apply ŌĆö when hitting an unexpected crash or error:**
1. Reproduce it reliably (run multiple times, with/without flags).
2. Read the stack trace and trace it to our code.
3. Read the actual code at the crash site.
4. Only after exhausting our code paths, consider toolchain issues.
5. If the error message mentions a specific Swift stdlib type (like `_ContiguousArrayBuffer`), check what *our* code passes to it, not what the stdlib does internally.

---

## 9. Test the cold path ŌĆö use the heart-path benchmark

**For any MEDIUM+ change touching pipeline / ASR / LLM / paste, run the heart-path benchmark before declaring the change complete.**

```bash
/wispr-rebuild-and-relaunch
scripts/heart-path-bench.sh --cold    # ~25 min, 5 samples, 5 min idle each
scripts/heart-path-check.sh           # compares to .validation/latency-baselines.json
```

Regression thresholds (enforced by `heart-path-check.sh`):
- **FAIL** if `polish_p50 > 2x baseline` (same model).
- **FAIL** if `total_p50 > 1.5x baseline` AND `total_p50 > 1500 ms`.

If the check fails, root-cause the regression. **Never** bump the baseline to hide a slowdown. If the slowdown is an intentional quality trade, update `.validation/latency-baselines.json` with a clear justification in the commit message.

**Quick hot-mode check** (`--hot`, ~2 min, back-to-back samples) is only for plumbing verification. Per the cold-path rule below, any latency claim or pre-release sign-off requires `--cold`.

### Why cold-path matters

For any cache-sensitive subsystem (LLM polish with KV cache, connection pool, JIT-warmed code, disk-cached assets), benchmarks must include a cold-path scenario: wait 3ŌĆō5 minutes between invocations so the cache rotates. Immediate-reuse benchmarks hide the real user experience.

**Why:** 2026-04-13 the Gemma4 fix (#272) passed a 10-sample real-audio benchmark with sub-second polish times and shipped. Saurabh used the v1.9.3 build in real dictation flow (minutes between utterances) and saw 7ŌĆō14s polish times consistently. The hot-cache sub-second case was a statistical outlier (KV cache holding the prompt from 30s prior). Shipping this was "testing in a bubble."

Saurabh's words: "the problem is testing in a bubble instead of testing with the end solution. When I tested it shortly after you completed it, it seemed fast, but now, after about five minutes, it is much slower."

**How to apply for LLM polish latency work:**
1. Run the hot benchmark to prove correctness.
2. Also run a cold benchmark: dictate once, wait 5 min, dictate again, wait 5 min, dictate again. Record polish times for each.
3. Report BOTH numbers. If cold is 10├Ś hot, that is the number users feel ŌĆö not the hot one.
4. For thinking-capable models, explicitly measure what fraction of polish time is reasoning overhead (capture `message.thinking` length and token generation rate).

**How to apply more generally:**
- Any cache-sensitive subsystem has a hot path and a cold path.
- Benchmarks running requests back-to-back measure the hot path only.
- Real user experience is dominated by the cold path when there's meaningful idle time between uses.
- Include idle-time between samples in any latency validation.

