## 1. Plan ŌåÆ Council ŌåÆ Grounded Review ŌåÆ Build ŌåÆ Codex for every code change

**Rule.** Every change to shipped product code follows this 10-step shape. Council critiques become INPUT to Grounded Review, not a separate revision pass. Plan is revised once against fact-checked feedback.

0. **Gate 0 ŌĆö Prior-context check.** Run `gh issue view <N> --comments` AND `grep -nE "#<N>([^0-9]|$)" .claude/knowledge/session-log.md`. Post one paragraph in chat: *"Prior context for #<N>: <decisions already made>."* If an adopted plan exists, use it ŌĆö don't redraft, don't re-run council. Enforced by `check-issue-prior-context.sh` (blocks plan-file writes) + `gate-gh-issue-view.sh` (blocks comment-less `gh issue view`). Skipping Gate 0 burned PR 330 (#329, 2026-04-17).
1. **Gate 0.5 ŌĆö User Rubric.** For any feature in epics #314 / #316 / #317 (user-visible) / #320 / #321, answer the 9-question User Rubric in the Preface section of `docs/feature-requests/TEMPLATE.md`, resolving each question against a named persona from `.claude/knowledge/personas.md`. Paste the 9 answers (or "User Rubric: N/A ŌĆö [epic] is internal-only") into the chat summary that precedes Gate 1. Skipping Gate 0.5 is how we shipped engineered-input test corpora in prior sessions (2026-04-17 #342) ŌĆö tests that asked "my shopping list is:" when no human actually dictates that way. Enforced by `check-rubric-answered.sh` (blocks plan-file writes without rubric answers for user-facing epics).
2. **Gate 1 ŌĆö Intent check.** Report: user benefit (in one persona's words), UX, value, preliminary scope (tier, files, size, unknowns). For any change that adds responsibility to an existing coordinator/manager/AppState OR introduces a new such type, also report in plain English: "This will live on \[X\] because \[reason\]. The alternative would be \[Y\] but \[trade-off\]." This is the founder's earliest leverage point on placement ŌĆö they cannot read code, but they can interrogate "why X and not Y?" before any code is written. Skip this sentence only if the change is purely prompt/copy/catalog/config (i.e. would mark `N/A` in plan ┬¦3b). "Proceed?" ŌĆö **STOP for approval.**
3. **Plan** ŌĆö use `docs/feature-requests/TEMPLATE.md`. Save as `docs/feature-requests/issue-<N>-<YYYY-MM-DD>-<slug>.md` before council. Rubric answers from Gate 0.5 must already be in the Preface section of this plan file before it is saved. **Before saving, also complete TEMPLATE.md ┬¦3b "Active-epic cross-check" (when an owner is named) AND ┬¦10 "Code reality check" (paste grep evidence for every named symbol / module-import claim / process-init claim / quoted literal).** Skipping these is the failure mode that produces grep-checkable structural mistakes ŌĆö Codex will catch them, but burning a grounded-review cycle on what a 60-second grep would have caught is the writer paying instead of paying attention. Ref: 2026-05-02 #574 session burned 3 council rounds + 2 grounded reviews on a plan that claimed `AudioCaptureProxy.pendingConfig` (real: `needsReinit`) and invented route labels ŌĆö every mistake was a grep away.
4. **Council ŌĆö ONE round.** Purpose: *"Here's our plan. Given our context, how do we strengthen it?"* GPT + Gemini, with the inline project preamble at the top of every call (see ┬¦2 below). For human-centric features (epics #314 / #316 / #320 / #321, plus user-visible #317), use the persona-roleplay pattern in ┬¦2 instead of the generic shape. Save raw council outputs to `/tmp/<scope>/{gpt,gemini}-critique.md` so step 5 can hand them to Codex.
5. **Grounded Review ŌĆö ONE round, council critiques as input.** *"Here's the unrevised plan + GPT's critique + Gemini's critique + the code. Fact-check it. Should we pivot?"* Codex (`codex exec`) with full codebase access, read-only sandbox. Template-driven (`.codex/grounded-review-template.md`). Two questions in order: **Q1 Direction** ŌĆö is the proposed structural choice right, or does the actual code suggest a pivot? Enumerate alternatives. **Q2 Fact-check** ŌĆö for each numbered council finding, verdict (TRUE / FALSE / PARTIAL / JUDGMENT-CALL) + grep-verified `file:line` evidence + recommended action. Output: PROCEED-AS-PLANNED / PROCEED-WITH-REVISIONS / PIVOT. See ┬¦14. Catches: missing types, wrong line references, false premises in council critique, scope miscounts, hidden dependencies, structural alternatives the council missed.
6. **Revise ŌĆö single pass.** Apply Codex's verdict + accepted council findings to the plan in one edit. If Codex says PIVOT, that supersedes the original plan; rewrite. If revisions are substantial enough that the plan no longer matches what Codex reviewed, re-run ┬¦5 ŌĆö do NOT loop back to council.
7. **Gate 2 ŌĆö Plan sign-off.** Present revised plan in plain English with blast radius (┬¦5, ┬¦6) and the council/Codex digest. "Any changes before build?" ŌĆö **STOP for approval.**
8. **Build.**
9. **Phase 3 ŌĆö 6-step validation.** Run `scripts/validate-pr.sh` ŌåÆ writes `.validation/runs/<timestamp>-<shortsha>/`, calls `scripts/check-validation.sh`. Sequence: logic tests ŌåÆ smoke ŌåÆ Live UAT ŌåÆ Codex code-diff ŌåÆ fix loop ŌåÆ push. Skip a step ŌåÆ write `skip-note.txt` BEFORE pushing OR escalate to Stage 2; no third option. Mechanics, `run.json` schema, full lane table, and sharp-terminology definitions (Smoke ŌēĀ Live UAT ŌēĀ Merge-ready) live in [pr498-phase3-validation.md](../knowledge/pr498-phase3-validation.md). "Smoke = UAT" is the bypass anti-pattern called out by `feedback_uat_gate_is_load_bearing.md` (PR #497).

**Why the council critique is INPUT to Codex, not a separate revision step.** Council reviewers (GPT + Gemini) make claims, not facts ŌĆö they read the plan in isolation and disagree on substance roughly half the time. Phase D #496 shipped after council disagreed on three of five questions; only Codex with code access settled them (snapshot-before-iterate semantics, lifetime stability of consumers, `package` vs `public` access). The prior shape (council ŌåÆ revise ŌåÆ grounded review ŌåÆ revise again) ran two revision passes against drifted feedback; collapsing into one revision against fact-checked feedback cuts plan churn. Ref: 2026-04-29 #319 Phase D execution. Cost: ~5ŌĆō15 min Codex runtime per cycle. Apply for MEDIUM+ tier and for any feature where council disagrees on substance; SMALL changes within the zero-blast-radius exception skip both council and grounded review per ┬¦1.

**Plain English at all human gates.** Gate 0, Gate 0.5, Gate 1, Gate 2, mid-task pivots, wind-down check-ins: frame in plain English (no class/file names, no protocol/API jargon, no bare tier labels). Self-check before presenting: could a non-coder catch me solving the wrong problem? If no, rewrite. Technical detail only after, and only if asked.

### Gate 0 bypass and adopted-plan handling

The `check-issue-prior-context.sh` hook blocks plan-file creation until prior context is read; the hook denial message prints the sentinel-touch path and 30-min expiry.

If prior context reveals an adopted plan (TEMPLATE.md section headers in a comment, or a link to `docs/feature-requests/issue-<N>-*.md`): read it, summarize *"Plan from <date>: <one paragraph>. Intent still matches?"*, then skip to Gate 2. Do not rewrite or re-run council. Revise in place if stale.

**Scope (code lane):** `Sources/`, `Tests/`, `Package.swift`, `.github/`, `scripts/`, release/CI configs, website code (`website/src/{layouts,components,pages,utils}/`, `website/astro.config.*`, `website/package.json`). Full plan/council/Codex/PR/CI flow.

**Scope (local artifacts):** `.claude/`, `CLAUDE.md`, `docs/`, `session-log.md`, memory, knowledge, benchmark scripts not shipped. Update in place.

**Scope (content lane):** `website/public/`, `website/src/content/`, `assets/`, `content-engine/`, `docs/launch-assets/`, any image/video/SVG anywhere, marketing copy, README prose. No council, no Codex, no plan file, no eval gate. Direct commit to main or lightweight PR with only `build-check`. Mixed PR with code-lane files ŌåÆ split or escalate. Ref: PR #370 (2026-04-19) stuck on polish-eval required checks that don't apply to asset diffs.

**Why:** Tier estimates are systematically biased toward SMALL. Multiple past sessions showed what felt SMALL becoming MEDIUM becoming LARGE only after council + codex pressure-testing. 2026-04-14 Gemma4 investigation: the "1-line catalog PR" was small by diff, but the rebuild cycle around it wedged audio and burned a morning. Skipping the process costs hours and erodes user trust in the software's stability, which directly hurts marketing/growth work Saurabh needs to be doing instead of bug-hunting.

### Narrow exception ŌĆö zero blast radius

Skip plan council. Still require 1 Codex round on the diff, 1 human sanity-check, and the tier-appropriate tests/rebuild per ┬¦8ŌĆō┬¦11.

Qualifies only if ALL of the following are true:

- **Size:** Ōēż 20 lines changed, Ōēż 3 files touched.
- **Shape:** no new symbols, types, protocols, or public APIs; no control-flow change; no new module dependencies; no migration, schema, or persistence change.
- **Surface:** change is confined to ONE of:
  - Model-catalog entries (adding a row to an existing enum/list of models)
  - LLM prompt strings (polish prompts, system prompts)
  - User-facing copy in `website/src/` or `Sources/` (button labels, tooltips, empty-state text, What's New entries)
  - Single-value config/constant updates (timeout bumps, threshold tweaks inside existing bounds)
  - Version/appcast bumps as part of release workflow
- **Reversibility:** reverting is a single-commit revert with no downstream cleanup.

If ANY condition fails ŌåÆ full process. If unsure which bucket a change falls into ŌåÆ full process. The exception is enumerated on purpose; expanding it requires an explicit rule change, not interpretation.

**Audit trail.** When the exception is used, the PR description must say: `council-skip: zero-blast-radius (<which bucket>)`. This creates a grep-able corpus so we can measure ŌĆö 30 days after adoption ŌĆö whether shortcut-tagged PRs regressed more than full-process PRs. If they did, the exception narrows or dies.

**Not a license to pattern-match.** "Feels like a catalog row" is not a catalog row. "It's just a prompt" is not a prompt change if it changes the extraction contract. When the bucket is ambiguous the answer is: full process.

**Why this exception exists.** The absolute form of ┬¦1 was generalized from one incident (#272 Gemma4 polish latency, 2026-04-13). The lesson from #272 was "benchmark the cold path" ŌĆö addressed by ┬¦13. Running GPT + Gemini on a model-catalog row (#281) does not prevent another #272; it produces overhead without defect reduction. The exception is narrower than the incident it addresses and will be measured.

**How to apply:**
- Default to the full process on every code change.
- Before taking the exception, verify ALL four conditions in writing in the PR body.
- When user says "just do it quickly," map their ask to one of the enumerated buckets ŌĆö if it doesn't map, reply with the conditions and ask them to confirm they still want to skip.
- The temptation to skip outside the enumerated buckets ("it's just a docstring in Swift source", "it's just a one-line paste-handler add") is the signal to run the process anyway.
- When unsure whether something is "shipped code" vs local, treat it as shipped.

**Supersedes:** prior tier-routing assumption that SMALL changes can skip council/codex. Tier routing still governs test obligations and runtime validation breadth, not the plan/council/codex gates themselves ŌĆö except for the enumerated zero-blast-radius exception above.

### Narrow exception ŌĆö Codex grounded review settles the only fork

Pure-architecture refactors with no user-visible surface (`User Rubric: N/A`) may skip council when Codex grounded review (┬¦14) returns a clean verdict and the only remaining forks are mechanical (target name, observability annotation, capture shape, type rename). In those plans, council adds ceremony, not signal ŌĆö GPT has documented complexity-drift risk on plans without a concrete user flow to anchor on; Gemini speculates against the same code Codex already grep-verified.

When skipping under this exception, the PR body must say: `council-skip: codex-grounded-review settled the only structural fork, no user surface, no design ambiguity remaining`.

**Disqualifiers ŌĆö council MUST run even if `User Rubric: N/A`:**

- The plan changes a workflow gate, plan-template field, validation lane, hook, memory rule, or any mechanism by which future plans get reviewed.
- The plan introduces or relies on a numerical target whose measurement definition could be read two reasonable ways.
- The plan introduces a fitness gate AND has not specified the earliest failure point at which the gate fires.
- The plan modifies CI workflow structure (jobs, required checks, runner labels).

**Why the disqualifiers exist.** Phase E (#502, 2026-04-30) was reviewed by Codex grounded review only; council was skipped under this exception. Phase E shipped a working PR-time architectural-fitness gate that the founder later flagged as workflow-misplaced (catches drift after work is done, not before). Workflow-position questions ARE design questions; Codex grep cannot answer "should this fire at PR time or pre-push?" because the answer depends on team cost curves, not the code. The disqualifiers route those questions back to council even when the surface looks "pure architecture."

**Not interchangeable with zero-blast-radius.** That exception is for tiny diffs in enumerated content buckets. This exception is for architecture-only plans where Codex's code-grounded verdict makes council redundant. Different shape, different bar, different audit trail.

For features in user-facing epics (#314 / #316 / #317 / #320 / #321), council still pays its way via persona-roleplay regardless of how concrete the design is.

Refs: PR #503 (Phase F SetupCoordinator extraction, 2026-04-30) clean council-skip; PR #504/#505 (Phase E architecture regression tests) where the exception was applied incorrectly and the rule was narrowed accordingly.

