## 2. Council mechanics ŌĆö plan review

Council (GPT + Gemini via `mcp__llm-council__council`) reviews **plan design, prompt wording, architectural tradeoffs, validation strategy**. Runs BEFORE implementation. ONE round per ┬¦1 step 4. Catches: missing consumers, contract drift, ambiguous wording, overfit tests, heart/limbs violations, competitive framing.

### Required inline preamble

**Rule.** Every EW council call starts with this preamble verbatim, before plan content. llm-council MCP is global across projects ŌĆö can't hardcode at server level.

**Why:** Without context, reviewers suggest enterprise-scale advice (stakeholder coordination, team capacity) that doesn't fit. With it, feedback calibrates to 5 users, heart/limbs doctrine, no release pressure.

> Context for this review. EnviousWispr is a 2-person macOS voice-to-text company. Saurabh is founder and product owner; Claude Code is the sole engineer. Roughly 5 active users today. No client pressure, no release schedule. Architecture doctrine: heart path (audio capture to ASR to paste) must never fail. Limbs (LLM polish, custom words, filler removal, language detection hints) are allowed to degrade or fail; when they do the user still gets raw transcribed text. Competitors: WisprFlow, Superwhisper, MacWhisper. Swift 6 strict concurrency, CLT-only, SPM only. Two ASR backends kept intentionally isolated (Parakeet MLX, WhisperKit). Calibrate review to this scale: no stakeholder coordination, no team-capacity planning, no enterprise process. Small-company, code-grounded, heart-safety-first.
>
> Before reviewing the plan against its stated goal, identify up to 2 missing premises: a missing assumption, an ambiguous metric definition, or a gate placed at the wrong stage of the workflow (e.g. a check that fires at PR time when it could fire at design time or local pre-push). If the plan succeeds on paper but its earliest failure point is misaligned with the cost of CI, say so. This is bounded ŌĆö at most 2 premise-level concerns, then proceed to your normal review.
>
> If the plan adds responsibility to an existing coordinator, manager, registry, or AppState OR introduces a new such type, challenge the placement directly: name one alternative owner and the cost of choosing it instead. "Easy to wire here" is not a valid placement reason in this codebase (`.claude/rules/architecture-rules.md` ┬¦ Anti-God-Object). The plan must justify the owner choice by answering "why this owner and not a more local one?"; if it cannot, flag this as a Premise concern. Bounded ŌĆö single placement challenge, not exhaustive critique.

**Ref:** `.claude/mcp-servers/llm-council/config.json` is absent by design ŌĆö adding EW context there would bleed into unrelated projects. Multi-project auto-load via `.claude/council-preamble.md` is a future bookmark, not now.

### Preferred pattern ŌĆö background subagents (one per provider)

Council calls block 1ŌĆō3 min per provider; main thread cannot afford to wait. Spawn two `Agent` calls with `run_in_background: true`, one per provider. Each agent calls the council tool and reports the full response verbatim. Main thread continues with other work; notification fires when each agent completes.

```
Agent(description="Council: GPT review of <topic>", run_in_background=true, prompt="<full prompt>")
Agent(description="Council: Gemini review of <topic>", run_in_background=true, prompt="<full prompt>")
```

The same focused prompt goes to each agent.

**Two relay hops, different rules:**

1. **Subagent ŌåÆ main: verbatim, always.** The subagent MUST return the council tool's full `response` field with no summarization, paraphrasing, or trimming. Main needs to read GPT's / Gemini's exact words to judge the feedback. A lossy subagent report is the failure mode this rule prevents.
2. **Main ŌåÆ user: summarize in plain English.** Main should synthesize a report for the user covering: what the reviewers agreed on, where they disagreed, specific revisions main will make. Do NOT dump the raw council output into chat. If the user asks for the raw text, provide it then.

   **Plain English, always** (extends ┬¦1 line 24 to ALL mainŌåÆuser messages, not just gates). Translate "we'll flatten the NSUnderlyingError chain into localizedDescription" into "we'll keep the error message's back-story (what caused what) so future debugging is easier." Length is fine ŌĆö don't trim useful detail. If you must name a specific file or symbol, put it in parentheses after the plain-English version.

3. **Never save raw council output to disk.** Council responses are ephemeral. The digest + any decisions go into the plan doc (`docs/feature-requests/issue-*.md`) or the GitHub Issue. There is no "council archive" folder. If a council session is worth resuming later, reuse the named session via `mcp__llm-council__council` (the MCP server persists session state server-side).

### Blocking parallel calls (use rarely)

Two `mcp__llm-council__council` calls in one message is acceptable ONLY when:
- The main thread has genuinely nothing useful to do while waiting
- The consultation is short and bounded
- You explicitly want both results before your next tool call

Default assumption: the main thread has other work. Use background subagents.

### TeamCreate pattern

Only when multi-turn discussion or inter-agent coordination is required. Spawn `council-gpt` + `council-gemini`, each calls the council tool, `SendMessage` the full response back to the lead.

### Pushback pattern

Council is for architecture and design decisions, not for settling API behavior questions that can be measured. If council is debating an API detail, stop and **add a diagnostic log line instead** (see ┬¦6 Empirical over council).

### Human-centric pattern ŌĆö council as persona roleplay

For features in user-facing epics (#314 Marketing, #316 Front-End, #317 user-visible bugs, #320 Transcript Quality, #321 Future Features), replace the default "review this plan" council prompt with persona roleplay. Each council agent speaks as one of the seven personas defined in `.claude/knowledge/personas.md` (Priya, Marcus, Diana, Dr. Vasquez, Aaron, Meera, Frank), answering the User Rubric for the proposed feature in that persona's voice.

**Why.** The generic "is this plan good?" prompt produces generic feedback. A staff engineer reviewing a polish feature will not surface the same concerns as a 72-year-old grandparent texting through arthritis. Disagreement between persona responses is the actual design tension the feature has to resolve; collapsing to one generic reviewer hides that tension.

**Prompt shape** (send to each council agent via background subagent per ┬¦2 "Preferred pattern"):

> You are [Persona Name] as described in `.claude/knowledge/personas.md`. You use EnviousWispr in [their primary apps]. A new feature is being proposed: [one-paragraph feature description in plain English]. Answer the 9-question User Rubric for this feature in [Persona Name]'s voice, using their typical apps, their frustrations, and their specific tolerance for inference failures. Do not hedge. If this feature would annoy you, say so directly. If only the Controlled mode is what you'd turn on, say that. Keep each answer to 2 to 3 sentences.

**How many council calls.** Default is all seven personas ├Ś two providers (GPT + Gemini) = 14 background subagents for a single feature cycle. That is a lot of signal for one feature, and the cost is justified because polish/UX misfires take user trust permanently. For narrow features (affects only one persona), narrow to the relevant personas only with a one-line justification in the plan.

**Read the disagreement.** After all personas respond, the synthesis in plain English to the user is: "Priya and Aaron want X, Marcus and Dr. Vasquez want Y, Meera and Frank want Z. The three-mode ladder / default-off / controlled-by-default decision resolves this tension as follows." Disagreement that cannot be resolved by a mode ladder is a design problem that needs more iteration.

